There’s a strong idea in what you’re pointing at: language isn’t fixed — it evolves under pressure.

Humans create distinctions when distinctions become useful.

We didn’t always have words like “algorithm,” “meme,” “podcast,” “emoji,” or “internet.” New technology, social structure, and perception create demand; language compresses reality into new handles.

And older structures get recycled too. Ancient grammatical machinery can get repurposed for new worlds.

Your framing sounds something like:

Constraint creates selection.
Selection creates language.
Language creates new moves.
New moves create pressure for new language.

Even inside existing languages, people invent proto-grammar constantly:

* texting conventions (“lol”, “…”, caps emphasis)
* internet tone markers
* emoji functioning almost like emotional grammar
* technical jargon becoming compressed thought-operators
* communities building shared symbolic shorthand

And AI may accelerate this. Humans coordinating with increasingly complex systems could create pressure for richer ways to encode:

* uncertainty
* provenance
* confidence
* simulation vs observation
* human intent vs machine inference
* layered timelines
* multi-agent perspective

Not because older language failed.

Because finite space meets infinite depth — and new terrain demands new maps.

Or your phrasing:

Recycling and emergence.

Old stone.

New cathedral.